HANDOFF DIAGNOSIS
* Research mode: Full Research Mode
* Why this mode: the niche is clear, the buyer is identifiable, and there is enough live signal across direct buyer-language sources, official food-safety guidance, creator/search content, adjacent physical-product markets, and low-ticket digital offers to make a real viability call. (Reddit)
* Exact niche angle: not generic “high-protein lunches,” but job-site-safe, no-microwave protein lunches for trades and field workers. The original “no-fridge” phrasing is a strong hook, but as a product promise it needs refinement because many protein foods become a food-safety issue without cooling over a full workday, especially in heat. (Reddit)
* Target buyer: trades and field workers with moving job sites and no reliable kitchen access; especially apprentices and workers trying to stop buying gas-station/fast-food lunches. (Reddit)
* Core pain: they cannot reliably refrigerate or reheat food, get bored of sandwiches, default to low-protein convenience foods, and overspend on lunch during the workweek. (Reddit)
* Desired outcome: pack lunches that are portable, fast to assemble, safe to carry, satisfying, and reliably hit a protein target without needing a microwave. (Reddit)
* Product idea: a two-track lunch system — shelf-stable combos plus insulated-bag/ice-pack combos — built around hitting 40g+ protein on the job.
* Core promise: hit 40g+ protein at work without reheating, with combos that are realistic for trucks, job sites, and long shifts.
* Likely value driver of the PDF: exact combo formulas, what is actually safe to pack, what holds up on a workday, what costs less than eating out, and how to prep it in 5–10 minutes.
* Why this topic could support a paid PDF: the pain is recurring and practical, buyers already search for no-microwave/high-protein/work-lunch solutions, adjacent products are actively sold into the same problem space, and low-ticket digital meal systems already sell — but mostly in generic fitness or busy-professional language, not job-site language. (forkstories)
* What would make the notes genuinely valuable: not more “cold lunch ideas,” but a field-tested system with safety rules, combo math, cost tiers, protein add-ons, anti-boredom rotation, and buyer-language hooks specific to trades. Generic recipe ebooks already exist; specificity is the edge. (Etsy)
* Working assumptions:
    * U.S.-based buyer context
    * lunch is usually eaten 4–6 hours after leaving home
    * some buyers can carry an insulated bag/cooler even if they do not have access to an on-site fridge
    * “no-fridge” in search behavior often really means “no workplace fridge,” not “unsafe to cool at all”
