RESEARCH NOTES

1. Market / Niche Specific Opportunity
* Observed: the opportunity is strongest where three pains overlap: no microwave, no on-site kitchen/fridge, and overspending on convenience food. That overlap appears repeatedly in construction, frugal, and budget-food threads. (Reddit)
* Observed: buyers do not need chef-level variety. Several posts explicitly say low effort is the goal and repeating the same meal is acceptable if it works. That makes a system PDF more natural than a recipe-heavy ebook. (Reddit)
* Observed: adjacent physical products are heavily marketed around the same work-lunch constraint: heated lunch boxes “for work/car/truck,” rugged worksite coolers, and job-site meal-heating gear. That is strong proof that the lunch-access problem is commercial, not imaginary. (TikTok Shop)
* Observed: the digital offer market exists, but it is generic. Etsy and Gumroad are full of “high-protein meal plans,” “no-cook meal plans,” and “high-protein lunch ideas for work,” but they are rarely built for field workers, safety constraints, or blue-collar routines. (Etsy)
* Inferred: the commercial opening is not invention; it is translation — taking existing protein-lunch logic and reworking it for trades language, workday survivability, and cost realism.
* whether the market looks durable, trendy, or fragile:
    * durable: lunch is a daily recurring pain
    * mildly trendy: “high protein” and “40g lunch” framing benefits from current nutrition/social momentum
    * fragile if positioned too broadly as meal prep content without field-worker specificity (YouTube)

